  "nursesNote": "Metformin is the first-line oral drug for type 2 diabetes; it lowers glucose production and does not cause hypoglycemia by itself, but can cause GI upset (take with food) and must be held before and after iodinated contrast dye because of the risk of lactic acidosis and kidney injury. Sulfonylureas (glipizide, glyburide) stimulate insulin release and CAN cause hypoglycemia, so the patient should not skip meals and should recognize low-blood-sugar signs (shaky, sweaty, confused, fast heart rate) and treat with a fast-acting carbohydrate. Other agents include GLP-1 agonists (names ending in -tide; weight loss, GI effects) and SGLT2 inhibitors (ending in -flozin; spill glucose in urine, raising UTI and genital infection risk). Lifestyle (diet, activity, weight) remains core therapy, and the nurse monitors blood glucose and A1C.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Give metformin with food and hold it before contrast dye",
    "Monitor for hypoglycemia with sulfonylureas",
    "Teach not to skip meals and to recognize low-blood-sugar signs",
    "Watch for UTI/genital infection with SGLT2 inhibitors",
    "Monitor blood glucose and A1C"
  ],
